---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import status from '../../data/_status.json';

const refresh = `${new Date(status.generated_at).toISOString().slice(0, 16).replace('T', ' ')} UTC`;
const sources = (status.sources as Array<{name: string; ok: boolean; records: number; duration_s: number; error: string | null}>).slice().sort((a, b) => b.records - a.records);
---
<Base title="Methodology" active="about">
  <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-3xl">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p>
      This tracker aggregates hantavirus reports from public-health authorities, outbreak
      surveillance networks, and peer-reviewed channels. Every datapoint on the map carries a
      <strong>confidence tier</strong>, a <strong>source</strong>, and a <strong>last-updated</strong>
      timestamp. We never paraphrase numbers — case and death counts are taken verbatim from the
      cited source.
    </p>

    <h2 id="tiers">Confidence tiers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Confirmed</strong> — published by a recognised public-health authority
        (CDC, WHO Disease Outbreak News, ECDC, PAHO, national or state ministry of health).
        Lab-confirmed where stated by the source.</li>
      <li><strong>Probable</strong> — outbreak investigation underway with lab-pending cases,
        or confirmed by a health authority but provisional in the source's own language.</li>
      <li><strong>Signal</strong> — picked up from <em>ProMED-mail</em> or <em>HealthMap</em>
        before authority confirmation. Useful for early awareness; treat as unconfirmed until
        upgraded.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>US data granularity</h2>
    <p>
      CDC releases hantavirus surveillance data at the state level only — county-level
      breakdowns are withheld to protect patient privacy (small N). US points on the map are
      therefore placed at state centroids, not specific addresses. Outside the US, granularity
      depends on the reporting authority.
    </p>

    <h2>Update cadence</h2>
    <p>
      A GitHub Actions workflow runs the ingest pipeline daily at 06:17 UTC. It fetches each
      source, normalizes to a common schema, and commits the resulting GeoJSON into this repo.
      The site is then rebuilt and deployed. Last build date is shown in the footer.
    </p>

    <h2>Cruise-outbreak analysis (daily-refreshing)</h2>
    <p>
      The cluster's figures come from whichever of two authorities published most
      recently: <strong>CDC HAN 528</strong> or the latest WHO Disease Outbreak News
      linked from the WHO emergency-event page <code>2026-E000227</code> (currently
      DON601, 13 May 2026). Each ingest run parses both, takes the freshest, and
      computes attack rate, CFR, days-since-departure, and days-since-source-update.
      If both parses fail, the section falls back to the verified 2026-05-08 snapshot
      — never to fabricated data — and the page surfaces a <code>Source live-parsed:
      yes/no</code> indicator plus an <code>as of (N days ago)</code> staleness badge
      so readers can see which mode they're looking at.
    </p>

    <h2>What we don't show</h2>
    <p>
      During the 2026-05-12 provenance audit, several state-level 2025 aggregates were
      removed because they originated from search-result snippets rather than from
      citable state ministry-of-health bulletins. We'd rather show three well-sourced
      records than five with a guess in the middle. State aggregates re-enter the
      dataset only when accompanied by a citable bulletin URL.
    </p>

    <h2 id="source-health">Source health (last ingest)</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-ink/70">
      Ingest last ran <strong>{refresh}</strong> — <strong>{status.summary.ok}/{status.summary.ok + status.summary.failed}</strong>
      sources reporting, <strong>{status.summary.records_total}</strong> raw records
      (after dedup: {status.total_records}). Total run time: {status.duration_s}s.
    </p>
    <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-ink/10 bg-white">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead class="bg-paper text-ink/70">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Source</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-right font-semibold">Records</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Status</th>
            <th class="px-3 py-2 text-right font-semibold">Time</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-ink/5">
          {sources.map((s) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="px-3 py-1.5"><code>{s.name}</code></td>
              <td class="px-3 py-1.5 text-right tabular-nums">{s.records}</td>
              <td class="px-3 py-1.5">
                {s.ok
                  ? <span class="text-emerald-700">ok</span>
                  : <span class="text-rose-700">{s.error ?? 'fail'}</span>}
              </td>
              <td class="px-3 py-1.5 text-right tabular-nums text-ink/60">{s.duration_s}s</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="text-xs text-ink/50">
      Sources marked <code>ok</code> with <code>0</code> records returned cleanly but had no
      hantavirus content this run (e.g., a weekly bulletin that didn't mention it).
      Stubs (Chile, ProMED, HealthMap, legacy WHO/CDC HAN listings) show 0 by design —
      see notes below.
    </p>

    <h2 id="sources">Active sources</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>CDC NNDSS</strong> via the data.cdc.gov SODA API (dataset
        <code>x9gk-5huc</code>) — weekly per-state HPS case counts for the
        current and previous year. This is the consistent federal aggregator
        and serves the US map markers.</li>
      <li><strong>CDC HAN 528</strong> via direct HTML scrape — primary source
        for the cruise cluster figures, consulted alongside WHO DON each run.</li>
      <li><strong>WHO event page</strong> <code>2026-E000227</code> + linked
        Disease Outbreak News articles (DON599 / DON600 / DON601 and any future
        DONs) — alternative authority for the cruise cluster; whichever of CDC
        or WHO is fresher provides the canonical figures.</li>
      <li><strong>ECDC Communicable Disease Threats Report</strong> via the
        <code>/en/taxonomy/term/1505/feed</code> RSS — weekly EU-wide threat
        bulletins that mention hantavirus.</li>
      <li><strong>Argentina BEN</strong> (Boletín Epidemiológico Nacional) —
        the Andes-virus endemic zone. We track the season-cumulative count
        published by the Ministerio de Salud.</li>
      <li><strong>New Mexico DOH</strong> — state-DOH page for NM, kept as a
        secondary citation when state-level figures diverge from federal NNDSS.</li>
      <li><strong>PubMed</strong> via NCBI E-utilities — academic signal layer
        (recent peer-reviewed papers indexed under the hantavirus MeSH term).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Sources we'd like but can't currently use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>ProMED-mail</strong> — discontinued its free public RSS in
        the 2023–24 funding crisis. Subscription-only.</li>
      <li><strong>Chile MINSAL</strong> — protected by Cloudflare's WAF;
        scripted access returns 403. Would require a headless browser.</li>
      <li><strong>WHO Disease Outbreak News listing</strong> — the legacy RSS
        endpoint is gone; the listing page is now a client-rendered SPA. We
        currently follow only the linked DONs from the cluster's emergency-event
        page, which captures the cruise cluster but not unrelated DONs.</li>
      <li><strong>HealthMap</strong> — public API discontinued.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What this tracker is not</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Not medical advice. If you suspect exposure, contact a clinician.</li>
      <li>Not authoritative-of-record — defer to your national or state health authority.</li>
      <li>Not real-time — there's a daily ingest cadence and authorities themselves report
        with delay.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If you spot a wrong count, missing report, or stale entry, please open an issue on the
      project's GitHub repository.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
